\begin{frame}{Investment styles}
The ESG focus has changed over time
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
\pause
\item Initially ESG investment was about avoiding companies with ESG issues
\begin{itemize}
\item Norwegian Petroleum Fund excluded 17 tobacco companies in January 2010
\end{itemize}
\item Now there is more focus on identifying firms with positive characteristics
\begin{itemize}
\item search for ESG factors
\item ESG may be linked to low volatility and value
\end{itemize}
\item There is increased attention on involvement in firms and influencing their behaviour
\begin{itemize}
\item Engine No. 1
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Theory}
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
\pause
\item Change the cost of capital to promote good and stifle bad
\begin{itemize}
\item this means lower returns for investors
\end{itemize}
\item ESG factors may suggest improved long-term performance
\begin{itemize}
\item but do these overshoot?
\end{itemize}
\item Activism may make the firm safer and more profitable
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

